            . I <rs id="t18290611-298-viclabel1574" type="occupation">keep an earthenware-shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-298-victim2171 t18290611-298-viclabel1574"></join>, in <placeName id="t18290611-298-crimeloc1575">Silver-place, New Road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-298-crimeloc1575" type="placeName" value="Silver-place, New Road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-298-crimeloc1575" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-298-off1572 t18290611-298-crimeloc1575"></join>. On the 10th of April I saw my jugs safe at half-past eight o'clock in the evening, and was showing them to a person - in a quarter of an hour I missed them, but did not see them taken - in about half an hour the watchman brought them - he asked if I had lost any thing - I told him I had lost two jugs; he then pulled them from under his coat.</p>
               <p>THOMAS FORD. I am a watchman. I saw the prisoner passing my beat at five minutes past nine o'clock, it<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182906110130"></xptr>is about two hundred yards from the prosecutor's - he had two jugs under his coat, and that induced me to stop him, as I had seen him before; he said he bought them, but could not say where, and was going to take them to his master - I thought it was not right, and took him to the watch-house - I went to the prosecutor who claimed them.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I hope you will have mercy on me. I have no friends.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 12.</p>
               <p>Recommended to Mercy by the Prosecutor.</p>
